%N A147680 Number of disk polyominoes of order n (see Comments for definition).
%C A147680 Any closed disk in the real plane includes a finite set (possibly empty) of points from the square lattice Z^2.
%C A147680 These roughly-circular patches of lattice points are connected by chains of adjacent lattice points (this is an easy theorem) and hence they form a special class of polyominoes, which I call "disk polyominoes".
%C A147680 It's quite easy to calculate which lattice points are within a given radius of a given center, but the inverse problem can be a little challenging.
%C A147680 That is, given a polyomino, determine whether it is a disk polyomino.
%C A147680 I have been enumerating small disk polyominoes, to see how many configurations are possible for various numbers of lattice points.
%C A147680 There is one disk polyomino for each of the orders 0, 1, 2 and 3; two for each of the orders 4, 5 and 6; only one for order 7; two each for orders 9 and 10; and three each for orders 11 and 12.
%H A147680 Martin Fuller, <a href="/A147680/b147680.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..1000</a>
%H A147680 Martin Fuller, <a href="/A147680/a147680.txt">Table of disk polyominoes for n = 0..1000</a>
%H A147680 Martin Fuller, <a href="/A147680/a147680.py.txt">Python program and explanation</a>
%e A147680 The following is a list of the polyominoes up through order 15 that have been shown to be disks.
%e A147680 We canonicalize a disk polyomino by translating, rotating, and reflecting it until the center of the disk is in the triangle with vertices (0, 0), (1/2, 0) and (1/2, 1/2); this is the fundamental domain of the symmetry group of the lattice Z^2.
%e A147680 Once the polyomino has been canonicalized, it can be represented uniquely as a list showing the number of cells on each horizontal row, starting with the topmost row. The uniqueness is due to the fact that each row must be "centered" at either x=0 (for odd rows) or x=1/2 (for even rows).
%e A147680 For each order, we sort the disk polyominoes into "lexical" order.
%e A147680 For order 0, we of course have only (0), and for order 1 only (1).
%e A147680 Order 2 gives (2), and order 3 gives the L-tromino (12).
%e A147680 Order 4 has two examples, the T-tetromino (121), and the block (22).
%e A147680 Order 5 gives the X-pentomino (131) and the P-pentomino (221).
%e A147680 Order 6: (222), (231).
%e A147680 Order 7: (232).
%e A147680 Order 8: (242), (332).
%e A147680 Order 9: (333), (342).
%e A147680 Order 10: (1342), (343), (442).
%e A147680 Order 11: (1343), (1442), (443).
%e A147680 Order 12: (13431), (1443), (2442), (444).
%e A147680 Order 13: (13531), (14431), (1444), (2443).
%e A147680 Order 14: (14441), (14531), (24431), (2444).
%e A147680 Order 15: (14541), (24531), (244421), (3444).
